"1160–1217":"1160–1217","1162–Female":"1162–Deceased","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1162":"1162","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1280":"1280","aprox 1230":"about 1230","1217":"1217","1228":"1228","1258":"1258","1202":"1202","1289":"1289","about 1202":"about 1202","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","of, Portugal":"Portugal","Castilla La Nueva Region, Spain":"New Castile, Spain","Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fernández","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Carlos, Luis, Jorge, Miguel, Fernando, Mario, Jesus, Pedro, Francisco.  Portuguese Ligia, Joao, Armanda, Godofredo, Wenceslao.","Spanish (<b>Fernández</b>): patronymic from the personal name   Fernando  . The surname (and to a lesser extent the variant   Hernandez  ) has also been established in southern Italy, mainly in Naples and Palermo, since the period of Spanish dominance there.","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the name in 1 above at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some Jewish descendants retained the surname that their families had adopted as Roman Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Fernando","meanings":["A modern form of the old Spanish name <i>Ferdinando</i>, which is of Germanic (Visigothic) origin, from <i>farð</i> ‘journey’ (or possibly an altered form of <i>frið</i> ‘peace’) + <i>nand</i> ‘ready, prepared’. The name was hereditary in the royal families of Spain from an early date. It was borne by  Ferdinand I  (  d. 1065 ) of Castile and Leon, who conducted successful campaigns against the Moors, and by his descendant  Ferdinand V  (  1452–1516 ), who finally expelled the Moors from Spain altogether; he also gave financial backing to Columbus. Through the marriage in  1496  of his daughter  Joan the Mad of Castile  to the Habsburg  Archduke Philip , the name Ferdinand also became hereditary in the Austrian imperial family. Their younger son, Ferdinand (  1503–64 ), acquired the succession to the kingdoms of Hungary and Bohemia by marriage in  1521 , and became Holy Roman Emperor in  1558 .  See  <b>Ferdinand</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"Pérez","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Anglo-Norman: Anglo-Norman forms of Peter."],"variants":[{"name":"Perrez","meanings":["Anglo-Norman: Anglo-Norman forms of Peter."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Fernández Pérez Portugales was born about 1202, in Portugal, his father, Segundo Pedro Ermíldez Portugalés, was 44 and his mother, Blanca Pantoja, was 42. He married Maria de Aceves de Toledo in 1228, in New Castile, Spain. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1280, in Spain, at the age of 79."},"et":{"about 1202–1280":"umbes 1202–1280","1202–1280":"1202–1280","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1230–1258":"1230–1258","1230–1289":"1230–1289","–1274":"–1274","–Female":"Surnud","1160–1217":"1160–1217","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1162":"1162","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1280":"1280","aprox 1230":"umbes 1230","1217":"1217","1228":"1228","1258":"1258","1202":"1202","1289":"1289","about 1202":"umbes 1202","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","of, Portugal":"Portugal","Castilla La Nueva Region, Spain":"New Castile, Hispaania","Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"about 1202–1280":"noin 1202–1280","1202–1280":"1202–1280","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1230–1258":"1230–1258","1230–1289":"1230–1289","–1274":"–1274","–Female":"Kuollut","1160–1217":"1160–1217","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1162":"1162","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1280":"1280","aprox 1230":"noin 1230","1217":"1217","1228":"1228","1258":"1258","1202":"1202","1289":"12